\#\# Technical Architecture  
  
| Layer                | Technology / Method                                                           |  
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- |  
| \*\*Blockchain\*\*       | Ethereum / Polygon (low gas, high TPS)                                        |  
| \*\*Token Standard\*\*   | ERC-721 (NFT) + ERC-1155 (batch minting, optional)                           |  
| \*\*Decentralized Storage\*\* | IPFS + Filecoin (persistence)                                            |  
| \*\*Content Addressing\*\* | CID (Content Identifier) + cryptographic hash verification                 |  
| \*\*Oracle\*\*           | Chainlink (for third‑party grading data or physical test results)             |  
| \*\*Frontend / SDK\*\*   | React + Web3.js, certificate verification portal                              |  
| \*\*Grading Data Input\*\* | Offline signing tool (HSM) for authorized BGI graders                       |  
  
---  
  
\#\# Core Technical Logic  
  
\#\#\# 1. Digital Mapping of Diamond 6C Data  
  
BGI describes 6C data using a standardized JSON Schema, including the grader’s signature:  
  
\`\`\`json  
\{  
  "version": "1.0",  
  "diamond\_id": "BGI-210394",  
  "carat\_weight": 1.24,  
  "color": "D",  
  "clarity": "VVS1",  
  "cut": "Excellent",  
  "fluorescence": "None",  
  "chain\_fingerprint": "0x7a3f...c9e2",  
  "grading\_lab": "BGI Hong Kong",  
  "grading\_date": "2026-04-01",  
  "grader\_signature": "0x9d2e..."  
\}
    • chain\_fingerprint : A hash of the diamond’s laser inscription and a high‑resolution microscopic image, ensuring a unique binding between the physical diamond and the certificate.
    • Grader signature : Signed with an HSM to guarantee data origin authenticity.
2. NFT Certificate Minting Process
    1. Physical grading – An authorized BGI grader measures the diamond using standard equipment and generates 6C data.
    2. Data signing – The grader signs the data package with their private key to prove authenticity.
    3. Upload to IPFS – The signed data package is uploaded to IPFS, obtaining a unique CID (Qm...).
    4. Mint NFT – Invoke the smart contract’s mintCertificate method with:
        ◦ Diamond CID
        ◦ Grader signature
        ◦ Owner wallet address
    5. On‑chain record – The smart contract mints an ERC-721 token, binding tokenId to the CID, and records the minting time and grader address.
3. Decentralized Storage & Content Addressing
    • Raw data (grading images, spectral data) is stored on IPFS.
    • Certificate metadata (compliant with ERC-721 Metadata extension) points to the IPFS CID.
    • Persistence guarantee – Via Filecoin storage deals or pinning services (e.g., Pinata) to prevent data loss.
    • Integrity verification – Anyone can recompute the hash of a downloaded certificate file using ipfs cid compute. If it matches the CID recorded on-chain, the certificate has not been altered.
4. Smart Contract Verification Mechanism
BGI’s smart contract provides the following core functions:
Function	Description
verifyCertificate(tokenId)	Returns the certificate CID, grader address, minting time, current owner
isCertificateValid(tokenId)	Checks whether the certificate is revoked or transferred (only latest owner)
transferCertificate(to, tokenId)	Transfers ownership (requires signature of current owner)
revokeCertificate(tokenId)	Only callable by contract admin (BGI multisig) – revokes a fraudulent certificate

On‑chain verification logic example (Solidity) :
function verifyCertificate(uint256 tokenId)  
    public view returns (bool, string memory, address)  
\{  
    Certificate storage cert = certificates\[tokenId\];  
    require(cert.exists, "Token does not exist");  
    require(!cert.revoked, "Certificate revoked");  
    return (true, cert.cid, cert.originalGrader);  
\}
Data Flow Diagram
\[Physical Diamond\] → \[Grader measures\] → \[6C data + signature\]  
                                    ↓  
                              \[Upload to IPFS\]  
                                    ↓  
                           \[Obtain CID & metadata URL\]  
                                    ↓  
\[User wallet\] ← \[Mint NFT certificate\] ← \[BGI smart contract\]  
                                    ↓  
                           \[Visible on public blockchain explorer\]  
                                    ↓  
\[Buyer/Retailer\] → \[Enter tokenId\] → \[Frontend shows certificate + verification status\]
Security & Privacy Design
    • Grader identity anchoring – Each grader’s public key is bound to an on‑chain DID (Decentralized Identifier) issued by BGI. Every certificate signature is verifiable.
    • Anti‑substitution via chain fingerprint – chain\_fingerprint is a hash of the diamond’s laser inscription and a microscopic image, ensuring the certificate is strongly bound to the physical diamond.
    • Privacy protection – Certificates contain no personal information (e.g., owner name); only wallet addresses are recorded. During retail transactions, Zero‑Knowledge Proofs (ZKPs) allow selective disclosure of attributes (e.g., “clarity ≥ VS2”).
    • Multisig governance – Core contract upgrades, batch revocations, etc., require approval by a 3/5 multisig wallet to prevent single points of failure.
User Guide
Verify a Diamond Certificate (no wallet needed)
    1. Visit bgi.xyz/verify
    2. Enter the tokenId from the diamond certificate or scan the QR code
    3. The page will display:
        ◦ Full 6C data
        ◦ Grader signature status (valid / invalid)
        ◦ Current owner’s wallet address (anonymous)
        ◦ Certificate minting time and number of blockchain confirmations
Mint a New Certificate (authorized graders only)
    • Grader logs into internal system → connects hardware wallet → uploads grading data → signature is generated automatically and the smart contract is called.
Transfer a Certificate (diamond owner)
    • Go to bgi.xyz/transfer → connect wallet → enter recipient address and tokenId → confirm transaction (pay a small gas fee).
Roadmap
    • Q2 2026 – Mainnet launch, support ERC-721 diamond certificate minting.
    • Q3 2026 – Integrate Chainlink oracle for real‑time exchange rates and on‑chain grading device data.
    • Q4 2026 – Launch Zero‑Knowledge Proof selective disclosure for high‑end auction house privacy transactions.
    • Q1 2027 – Cross‑chain interoperability (BNB Chain, Solana) for multi‑chain certificate compatibility.
